  "prompt": "How does end to end encryption work in WhatsApp?",
  "response": "WhatsApp uses end-to-end encryption (E2EE) based on the Signal Protocol, developed by Open Whisper Systems. Here's how it works:\n\n1. Key Generation\n- When you first install WhatsApp, a pair of cryptographic keys are created:\n  - Public key\n  - Private key\n- The public key is shared, while the private key remains on the device\n\n2. Key Exchange (Handshake)\n- When two users start a conversation, their devices exchange public keys\n- This creates a unique encryption key for that specific conversation\n- Each message is encrypted with a unique session key\n\n3. Encryption Process\n- When you send a message, it's encrypted on your device\n- Only the recipient's device can decrypt the message\n- WhatsApp servers cannot read the message content\n\n4. Verification\n- Users can verify encryption by scanning a QR code or comparing a unique security code\n- This confirms no man-in-the-middle interception\n\n5. Implementation Details\n- Uses 256-bit AES symmetric encryption\n- Messages, voice calls, video calls, and file transfers are encrypted\n- Keys are stored only on user devices, not on WhatsApp servers\n\nThis approach ensures that only the sender and intended recipient can read the messages.",
